    "body": "hey @ansermino .\r\n\r\nI'm not a license expert or lawyer or anything.\r\n\r\nReally, I just noticed etherem/web3 uses LGPL and got curious and did a bit of googling on the subject and thought I'd spur discussion. :)\r\n\r\nMy lay interpretation is that it may be overkill to use GPL for web-based libraries in many cases, because it would mean that any website incorporating this codebase would need to GPL their entire frontend (or at least the js bits).\r\n\r\nThe LGPL seems to be like the GPL for any derivative versions of the codebase (eg: if a company wants to fork lodestar to add new features that fork must be LGPL), but stops short of software that \"uses\" the codebase (eg: a website that includes lodestar as part of a larger webapp does not need to be LGPL).\r\n\r\nNot super familiar with the finer details or any gotchas, though, so I'm sure this would have to get cleared with \"the legal dept\".",
